Checklist to ship a palette
 ->Primary hue chosen (brand intent matched)
 ->Secondary & accent chosen (harmonious + useful)
 ->Neutral palette defined for backgrounds/text/surfaces
 ->CSS variables (tokens) created
 ->Contrast ratios checked (WCAG) for text & components
 ->Color-blind and grayscale checks passed
 ->States (hover/active/focus/disabled) defined
 ->Small style guide written for developers/designers
 ->Tested on devices and iterated


Quick TL;DR

Pick 1 primary brand color.

Add 1–2 secondary support colors.

Add neutral colors (backgrounds, text).

Add 1 accent for CTAs/alerts.

Check contrast (WCAG) and color-blind readability.

Create tokens (CSS variables) and sample states (hover/active/disabled).

Test on devices and iterate.

Step-by-step process
1 — Start with objective & audience

Purpose: e-commerce? corporate? blog? portfolio? dashboard?

Audience: age, culture, accessibility needs (older users need higher contrast), local color meanings.

Emotion: trust (blue), energetic (orange), luxury (dark purple/black), calm (greens).

Why it matters: colour choices should support business goals (e.g., “trust” for banking, “action” for CTA).

2 — Gather inspiration and constraints

Look at competitor sites and note color patterns you like.

Pick 2–3 reference images or brands for mood.

List constraints: brand color(s) already fixed? must match existing logo? corporate brand guidelines?

Tools: Coolors, Dribbble, Behance, Pinterest.

3 — Choose a primary color

The main brand color used for logo, primary CTAs, highlights.

Pick a hue consistent with your brand emotion.

Choose one good base tone (not too saturated, not too light).

Example: #1E90FF (vivid blue) or #2D8A6E (forest green).

4 — Generate supporting colors (secondary + accent)

Secondary color(s): used for secondary buttons, illustrations, accents. Choose complementary or analogous hues to the primary.

Accent color: bright contrast for call-to-action if primary is subtle — e.g., orange or magenta.

Palette strategies:

Monochrome — variations of one hue (safe, minimal).

Analogous — adjacent hues on the wheel (harmonious).

Complementary — opposite hue for high contrast CTAs.

Triadic — three evenly spaced hues for lively palettes.

5 — Define neutral palette (backgrounds, text)

Backgrounds: light neutrals for light theme (#ffffff, #f6f7f8), or dark neutrals for dark theme (#0f1113, #121417).

Text: high-contrast dark (#111827) or light (#f5f7fa). Use multiple levels:

--text-primary (main body text)

--text-secondary (muted text)

--muted (helper text)

Borders / dividers: subtle neutral (e.g., #e6e7e9).

6 — Set color proportions (how often to use each)

A common rule:

Neutrals: 60–80% (backgrounds, large areas)

Primary: 10–20% (brand presence)

Secondary: 5–10% (supporting UI)

Accent: 1–5% (CTAs, important highlights)

This preserves balance and makes your accent color noticeable.

7 — Assign colors to website parts (practical mapping)

Page background: --bg (light or dark neutral).

Surface / cards: --surface (slightly different neutral).

Primary text: --text-primary.

Secondary text: --text-secondary.

Primary CTA background: --primary (primary color).

Primary CTA text: usually white or dark depending on contrast.

Secondary CTA / ghost buttons: border --primary, text --primary.

Nav bar: can be --surface or --primary depending on design.

Links: --link (often primary or a darker tint).

Error / success / warning: standard red/orange/green (--danger, --success, --warning).

Focus outlines / accessibility indicators: visible contrasting color (often --primary or #ffb900).

Overlays / modal backdrop: rgba(0,0,0,0.5) for dark backgrounds.

8 — Ensure accessibility: contrast & color blindness

Contrast ratios (WCAG):

Normal text: ≥ 4.5:1 (AA)

Large text (≥18pt or 14pt bold): ≥ 3:1

UI components & graphical objects: ≥ 3:1

Tools: WebAIM Contrast Checker, Axe, Lighthouse (Chrome), Contrast (macOS), Stark plugin (Figma).

Color blindness: Check palettes in grayscale and simulate deuteranopia/protanopia/tritanopia using tools (Color Oracle, Sim Daltonism, Stark). Avoid relying solely on color to convey information — add icons/labels.

9 — Create color tokens and CSS variables (single source of truth)

Create semantic variables (not just hexes) so you can update easily.

Example CSS variables:

:root{
  --bg: #ffffff;
  --surface: #f6f7f8;
  --text-primary: #111827;
  --text-secondary: #6b7280;
  --primary: #1E90FF;
  --primary-600: #1b7fe6;
  --accent: #ff7a59;
  --success: #16a34a;
  --danger: #dc2626;
  --muted: #e6e7e9;
  --focus: #ffb400;
}


Use these tokens in your components, e.g. background: var(--surface); color: var(--text-primary).

10 — Define states: hover, active, disabled, focus

For each interactive color, define states (slightly darker/lighter or different opacity).

Example for primary button:

Normal: --primary

Hover: --primary-600 (darker)

Active: --primary-700

Disabled: --muted (low contrast), text --text-secondary

11 — Test on devices and environments

Test on mobile, tablet, desktop screens.

Test in bright sunlight (for mobile).

Test with browser zoom and high-contrast OS mode.

Test with users if possible.

12 — Document the palette & usage (design tokens + README)

Create a short style guide:

Show each color swatch, hex/RGB, purpose, contrast ratio with primary text.

Document when to use primary vs secondary vs accent.

Add DOs and DON'Ts.
